\begin{verbatim}
exponential(N, exponential_end = 0.01)
\end{verbatim}
Create an exponential window. exponential\_end = 1 is a uniform window.

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{N}: Number of points


\item \texttt{exponential\_end}: End value of the exponential window (0 < exponential\_end <= 1)

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Output}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{w}: Exponential window

\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
force(N, width = 0.1, exponential_end = 0.01)
\end{verbatim}
Create a force window according to Ref.[1].  For modal testing the exponential\_end should be the same in the force and in the exponential window.

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{N}: Number of points


\item \texttt{width}: Width (fraction) of the force window (between 0 and 1)


\item \texttt{exponential\_end}: End value of the exponential window (0 < exponential\_end <= 1)

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Output}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{w}: Force window

\end{itemize}
\textbf{Note}

\texttt{exponential\_end = 1} does not apply any exponential decay.

\textbf{Reference}

[1] W. A. Fladung and R. W. Rost. Cause and effect of applying the exponential window to an impact force signal. In Proceedings of IMAC XIV. Orlando, United States. 1996.

