\textbf{Note} The welch function is already implemented in \texttt{DSP.jl} under the name \texttt{welch\_pgram}. The function \texttt{welch} is implemented here for pedagogical purposes.

\begin{verbatim}
tfestimate(input_signal, output_signal, bs::Int, window_input = hanning(bs),
           window_output = window_input; fs::Int = 1, overlap = 0., type = :h1)
\end{verbatim}
Estimation of the one-sided transfer function between two signals

\textbf{Inputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{input\_signal::Vector\{Real\}}: Input signal


\item \texttt{output\_signal::Vector\{Real\}}: Output signal


\item \texttt{bs::Int} Block size


\item \texttt{window\_input}: Window function for the input signal


\item \texttt{window\_output}: Window function for the output signal


\item \texttt{fs::Int}: Sampling rate


\item \texttt{overlap::Real}: Overlap ratio between the segments


\item \texttt{type::Symbol}: Type of transfer function to estimate

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{:h1} (default)


\item \texttt{:h2}


\item \texttt{:h3} - h3 = (h1 + h2)/2


\item \texttt{:hv} - hv = sqrt(h1*h2)

\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Outputs}

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{H}: Transfer function


\item \texttt{freq}: Frequency range


\item \texttt{coh}: Coherence

\end{itemize}
